148 39-2-18.3.
149 (a) The conditions of employment, including work schedules, for a child performer shall
150 not be detrimental to such minor's health, well-being, and education and shall include
151 required breaks for meals, rest, recreation, and education and any request for a break by the
152 minor, the minor's parent or guardian, or a representative of the Department of Labor when
153 in the interest of the minor.
154 (b) Notwithstanding any other provisions of this chapter to the contrary, the scheduling
155 restrictions for a child performer employed or permitted to work rendering artistic or
156 creative services shall be, at a minimum, as follows:
157 (1) No infants between birth and 15 days shall be permitted to be employed or permitted
158 to work;
159 (2) A minor between 15 days and six months old shall not start work before 9:30 A.M.,
160 shall not work more than 20 minutes per day, shall not be at a location for more than two
161 hours per day, and shall not work past 8:00 P.M.;
162 (3) A minor between six months and two years old shall not start work before 7:00 A.M.,
163 shall not work more than two hours per day, shall not be at a location for more than four
164 hours per day, and shall not work past 7:00 P.M.;
165 (4) A minor between two and six years old shall not start work before 7:00 A.M., shall
166 not work more than three hours per day, shall not be at a location for more than six hours
167 per day, and shall not work past 7:00 P.M.;
168 (5) A minor between six and nine years old shall not start work before 7:00 A.M., shall
169 not work more than four hours per day, shall not be at a location for more than eight
170 hours per day, and shall not work past 10:00 P.M.;
171 (6) A minor between nine and 16 years old shall not start work before 7:00 A.M., shall
172 not work more than five hours per day, shall not be at a location for more than ten hours
173 per day, and shall not work past 10:00 P.M. on a school night or 12:30 A.M. on a
174 nonschool night; and
